 Quick Solution (Short Version)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If you just want the answer fast, here are the only 3 commands you need:

```bash
gdb ./debugger0_a
disas main
p/d 0x86342
```

Or if you want to actually run the program and read `eax` live from the register:

```bash
gdb ./debugger0_a
break main
run
stepi
stepi
stepi
p/d $eax
```

`stepi` = **step one instruction** at a time  
 `$eax` = read the value currently inside the eax register

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Key Concepts Learned
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Concept |                         | What it means |
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Binary / Executable               | A compiled program the CPU can run directly 
| GDB                               | A tool to pause and inspect a running program 
| Disassembly                       | Converting binary code into readable assembly instructions 
| Assembly                          | Low-level instructions the CPU follows (like `mov`, `push`, `ret`) 
| Register (eax)                    | A tiny storage slot inside the CPU 
| Hexadecimal                       | A base-16 number system used in low-level programming (0x prefix) 
| p/d                               | GDB command to print a value as a decimal number 
